did.unittitle: Young Women's Christian Association (YWCA) of Durham, NC records
did.abstract: The Young Women's Christian Association (YWCA) of Durham was founded in 1920 and served the larger Durham community from the 1920s until the 1970s. The Harriet Tubman branch of the Durham YWCA served the African-American community in particular and, through collaboration with the Central branch, fostered integration in a racically segregated Durham. In the 1970s, the YWCA became the home of the Durham Women's Health Co-op and the Durham Rape Crisis Center, which operated out of the YWCA Women's Center. These organizations were central to reform movements throughout Durham, from women's health and childcare to fair wages and civil rights. The YWCA of Durham records reflect both the administrative history of the YWCA, as well as the programs, projects, social events, and community outreach that formed the backbone of the organization. For example, a series of scrapbooks, put together by Y Teen groups, program participants, and residents of the YWCA's boarding houses captures the strength of the YWCA community. The broader impact of the YWCA is evident in their range of programming, especially the clubs they hosted, from PMS and Single Mothers groups to a "Matrons Club." The YWCA's impact is also reflected in administrative and financial materials that tell the story of the Y's work to serve the people of Durham that needed a safe place to build community for themselves and their families.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The collection is arranged into three series: Administrative, Program, and Community Outreach.

scopecontent.head: Collection Overview

The Harriet Tubman branch of the Durham YWCA served the AfricanAmerican community in particular and, through collaboration with the Central branch, fostered integration in a radically segregated Durham. In the 1970s, the YWCA became the home of the Durham Women's Health Co-op and the Durham Rape Crisis Center, which operated out of the YWCA Women's Center. These organizations were central to reform movements throughout Durham, from women's health and childcare to fair wages and civil rights. For example, a series of scrapbooks, put together by Y Teen groups, program participants, and residents of the YWCA's boarding houses captures the strength of the YWCA community. The broader impact of the YWCA is evident in their range of programming, especially the clubs they hosted, from PMS and Single Mothers groups to a "Matrons Club." The YWCA's impact is also reflected in administrative and financial materials that tell the story of the Y's work to serve the people of Durham that needed a safe place to build community for themselves and their families.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Files from the Executive Office of YWCA Durham, including the Harriet Tubman Branch and the files of Dorothea Burton, Carolyn Greene, Geraldine Mitchell, and Rupart Blanchard Includes materials such as reports to national, financial papers, building repairs and building addition reports/finanacal campaigns, basic standards of the YWCA, board meeting minutes and attendance sheets, United Fund correspondence and budgets, World YWCA materials, Operation Breakthrough proposals and funding, various pamphlets for women's programs, self study, association review, program priorities, personnel contracts and committee materials, and National Statistical Reports.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Files of former president's of YWCA of Durham including Czerni Brasuell, Viven Patterson Includes materials such as program reports, board minutes, board elections and resignations, national public affairs/policy newsletters, Women of Achievement nominations and awards, United Way board materials, leadership development files, Durham YWCA newsletters, budgets, mailing list materials, community events and resources, 5K race details and organization, and various program information.

odd.head: General
odd.p: Maud Cuney Hare of Boston writes to the "Secretary of the YWCA" to ask to book a "costume recital" in Durham. She writes, "Our new program is an especially attractive one, in that the first part is given in constume true to the Orient and the Tropics - the music is that of the darker races." Cuney writes that they've "been accepted by a white manager" who has booked them for white Women's Clubs.

odd.head: General

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Community Outreach series consists of records from the Durham Women's Health Cooperative and the Rape Crisis Center of Durham as well as those related to general outreach programming. They consist of informational pamphlets, training materials, flyers, periodicals, excerpts from periodicals, legislative summaries, administrative records, and newsletters.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Durham Women's Health Cooperative became attached to the Young Women's Christian Association (YWCA) in the 1970's. The records encompass correspondence with other women's health organizations, informational pamphlets, healthcare provider surveys, training materials, periodical excerpts and full-length periodicals on women's health issues, legislative summaries, and administrative records. Although the Durham Women's Health Cooperative primarily focused on women's health concerns, the records from the organization also include informational pamphlets and trainings around men's health topics, such as sterilization. A notable feature of the collection are the Doctor and Consumer Surveys; they are anonymous reviews of different health practioners in the area that give a perspective of women's experience of health care.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Rape Crisis Center of Durham became part of the Durham YWCA in the early 1980s. It provided counseling and response to victims of sexual abuse, assault and rape. There is also information about other organizations in North Carolina who support or treat victims of sexual violence who are of any age. The subseries notably includes information about various populations who may be at particular risk of experiencing sexual violence, including people with disabilities or children. The subseries includes administrative files, secondary research, handouts, pamphlets, and newspaper clippings.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains the various periodicals that the YWCA collected and provided as a public resource. The YWCA and the Women's Health Co-op each subscribed to various newsletters and periodicals from national and local organizations with related missions to the YWCA and the Women's Health Co-op. The Women's Health Co-op periodicals were available as a library of sorts available to the public.
